ity in Greece, 1945-1947 -- tOrganizing World Peace. The International Labour Organisation from the Second World War to the Cold War -- tConclusion -- tContributors to this Volume -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aWhen World War II ended, Europe was in ruins. Yet politically and socially, the years between 1943 and 1947 were a time of dramatic reconfigurations that proved to be foundational for the making of today's Europe. This volume homes in on the crucial period from the beginning of the end of Nazi rule to the advent of the Cold War. It demonstrates how the everyday experiences of Europeans during these five years shaped the transition of their societies from war to peace. The essays explore these reconfigurations on different scales and levels with the purpose of enhancing our understanding of how wars end.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0https://www.aup.nl/en/publish/open-access  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aJewszEuropexMigrationsxHistoryy20th century. 0aPeace of mindxReligious aspects. 0aRefugeeszEuropexHistoryy20th century. 0aReligion and social problems. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xCivilian reliefzEurope. 4aConflict and Peace. 4aHistory, Art History, and Archaeology. 4aHistory. 7aHISTORY / Military / World War II.2bisacsh1 aCerovic, Masha, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDenis, Juliette, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDullin, Sabine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDupas, Jean-Claude.1 aGribaudi, Gabriella, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHoffmann, Ste